#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Another method of calculating real GDP involves converting nominal GDP to real GDP by using the GDP deflator, which tracks price changes of a nation’s output over time. Canada’s GDP deflator for its base year of 2008 was $100$, since this is the year against which prices are compared. By 2015 the deflator had increased to $113$, indicating that the average prices of Canada’s output had increased by $13\\%$. By expressing 2015’s output in 2015 prices, therefore, Canada’s output would appear to have increased by $13%$ more than it actually did. Canada’s nominal GDP, which has been “inflated” by higher prices, can be “deflated” by dividing the country’s nominal GDP of $\\$2,040$ by the deflator expressed in hundredths, Canada’s real GDP can be approximated using this method. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Canada's real GDP can be calculated by weighting final  goods and services by their prices in a base year (a method that resulted in a real GDP of $\\$1,775$) or by dividing nominal GDP by the GDP deflator price index in hundredths (a method that resulted in a real GDP of $\\$1,805$). Either method is considered valid, but the deflator method is more likely to account for price changes of particular goods produced by a nation between a base year and the current year."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "For example, if between 2009 and 2015 the average price of a Canadian-made hockey stick fell from $\\$100$ to $\\$50$, and Canada produce $1m$ hockey sticks in 2009 and only $0.8m$ in 2015, the real output of hockey sticks would have appeared to have increased (since the base year price was actually higher than the current year price). In this way, weighting output using base year prices can cause a country’s GDP can be overstated. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp</a>.
