# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid ""
"Goods produced | 2017 price | 2017 quantity | 2018 price | 2018 quantity \n"
"- | - | - | - | -\n"
"Chocolate | $\\$2$ | $400$ | $\\$2.20$ | $400$\n"
"Cheese |  $\\$6$ | $200$ | $\\$8$ | $250$\n"
"Watches |  $\\$20$ | $80$ | $\\$25$ | $100$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Here’s another way to think about this: if we add up all of the output that was produced in Canada during 2015 using the prices that these goods sold for in 2008, the value of GDP in Canada is $\\$1.775$ Trillion. But if we add up all of the output that was produced in Canada during 2015 using the prices that they sold for in 2015, the value of GDP in Canada is $\\$2.04$ trillion. This means prices must have increased between 2008 and 2015. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid ""
"However, there is a slight problem with this method. Calculating real GDP by weighting final goods and services by their prices in a base year can lead to an overstatement of real GDP growth since the prices of some goods decrease over time. This overstates growth in real GDP because it makes it seem like goods make up a bigger share of spending than they really do. \n"
"[have as a drop down explanation]. In other words, if the price of a good is going down, (if it has gotten cheaper to produce) then using a price from long ago when it was really expensive would make it seem like a bigger deal in GDP that it really is."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "If current prices are higher than they were in previous years then a country’s nominal GDP will overstate the actual change in output that occurred, since it will be inflated by higher prices. On the other hand, if current prices are lower than in previous years, then nominal GDP will understate the actual change in output, since the value will be deflated by lower prices."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/economic-iondicators-and-the-business-cycle/real-vs-nominal-gdp/a/lesson-summary-real-vs-nominal-gdp</a>.
