#: intl/datastore:1
msgid ""
"Term | Definition\n"
"-|-\n"
"**nominal GDP** | the market value of the final production of goods and services within the geographic borders of a country in a given period using that year’s prices (also called “current prices”); for example in 2017 the value of the United States’ total output of all goods and services equaled $\\$19,495$ billion, which equals quantity of goods and services produced in 2017 times the 2017 prices of those goods and services (source: FRED database)\n"
"**real GDP** | nominal GDP adjusted for changes in the price level; more formally: the value of the final production of goods and services within the geographic borders of a country in a given period using prices from a base year (constant prices); real GDP adjusts the level of output for any price changes that may have occurred over time; for example, the United States’ real GDP for 2017 was $\\$17$ trillion (in 2009 prices); this tells us that between 2009 and 2017 prices in the US increased, resulting in a nominal GDP that is larger than the real GDP; real GDP ignores price increases by measuring output in prices from 2009\n"
"**GDP deflator** | a price index used to adjust nominal GDP to get real GDP; the GDP deflator measures the average prices of all finished goods and services produced within a nation’s borders over time; for example, the United States’ GDP deflator for 2017 was $113$, and for 2009 it was $100$, which tells us that 2009 was the base year and prices of finished goods increased by $13%$ between 2009 and 2017; the GDP deflator $=\\dfrac{\\text{nominal GDP}}{\\text{real GDP}}$ (Source: FRED database)\n"
"**base year** | the year used for comparison in the determination of price changes using the GDP deflator price index; for example, the base year that is currently used to adjust nominal GDP to real GDP in the United States is 2009. The deflator in a base year is always equal to $=100$\n"
"**current prices** | the prices at which goods are sold in a nation in a particular year; current prices are used when calculating nominal GDP\n"
"**constant prices** | the prices from a base year that are used to calculate real GDP in other years; for example, the United States uses prices from 2009 when calculating real GDP in subsequent and previous years; this allows for a more accurate measure of how a country’s actual output changes over time since using constant prices cancels out any changes in the price level between years"
msgstr ""

