# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid ""
"- The PPC can be used to illustrate the concepts of scarcity, opportunity cost, efficiency, underutilized resources, and economic growth or contraction. \n"
"- The shape of the PPC depends on whether opportunity costs are constant, increasing, or decreasing.\n"
"- The PPC can shift due to changes in factors of production as well as changes in productivity/technology. \n"
"Economic growth results in an outward shift of the PPC."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Because we are all faced with choices, we are all faced with opportunity costs. A wise man once said, “opportunity cost is the opportunity lost”. As you are getting ready to head to college, what are the explicit costs (the amount of money you have to plunk down to go to college like tuition, textbooks, and pens)? But there are many more costs - things you are giving up that you don’t actually pay for. Can you think of what some of those might be?"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Figure 1: Maxistan’s choices of what to produce"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "However, if they were able to acquire more of a resource, like more workers, they could now produce more of both goods. This would be what we refer to as **economic growth**. We can show the ability to produce more as a shift out of the PPC, as shown by the movement from the initial $PPC_1$ to a new $PPC_2$ as shown in Figure 3."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Let’s start with the assumption that Maixstan is initially producing combination D (9 hoverboards and 8 oranges) shown in Figure 1. Maxistan wants to make more oranges, so they decide to re-allocate their resources toward making more oranges. Going from combination D to combination C (making 4 hoverboards and 19 oranges), they give up 5 hoverboards to gain 5 tons of oranges. This means that going between those two points, the **opportunity costs** of each ton of oranges gained is a hoverboard."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Let’s think about what is going on as the country makes more and more oranges. Initially, the oranges are being grown outside in beautiful orange groves and the hoverboards are made in hoverboard factories. But as more and more resources are devoted to growing oranges, now Maxistan has to start growing oranges everywhere: on the rooftops of factories and on land not suited for growing oranges. Maxistan can eke out a few more oranges but as it closes the hoverboard factories and converts them into orange trees, they will be having to give up a lot just for a few more oranges. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Now, not only can Maxistan produce the combination that they wanted to, they could even produce a little more of either good."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Now, suppose that Maxistan is happily and **efficiently** producing combination D. All of a sudden, for some reason half of the hoverboard factory workers are sent home and now they are only producing 4 hoverboards and 8 tons of oranges, which we will call combination E and show on our PPC in Figure 2."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Previously we showed how the PPC illustrates scarcity, but it can do so much more than that! Let’s go back the problem of your pen running dry. Now that you know that this is a possibility, you have to make choices about what to do with that ink. Do you write that prize-winning essay? Or a love letter? What are you giving up if you choose the essay?"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Suppose that Maxistan wants to produce $8$ tons of oranges and $12$ hoverboards. Well, right now, that is just impossible. Unless they get more resources or improve technology, they are limited to producing only $9$ hoverboards if they make $8$ tons of oranges."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "They aren’t using all of their labor resources, so this means they are producing an **inefficient** amount of goods. They could put those workers back to work in the hoverboard factory and return to combination D, or retrain them to be orange grove workers and go to combination C, but in the meantime, these labor resources are being wasted. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "To see how the PPC can help us make decisions about scarcity and what we give up to get something, let’s head back to Maxistan and the decision to make hoverboards or oranges."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-opportunity-cost-efficiency-and-growth</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "What if they want *even more* oranges? In fact what if they decide that this is all they want to produce? Then going from combination C to combination A, they give up 4 hoverboards and only gain 1 orange. The opportunity cost of that oranges is 4 hoverboards, which was quite a bit more than before!"
msgstr ""

