# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "For example, suppose that we know that Maxistan devotes a lot of resources to making oranges and a some of their resources to producing hoverboards, which means they produce $13$ tons of oranges and $4$ hoverboards (let’s call that combination C). Or, they can devote a little bit to both and produce $8$ oranges and $9$ hoverboards (let’s call this combination D). We could show each of these on our graph, as shown in Figure 2."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Imagine that Maxistan wants to devote absolutely all of its resources to making oranges, which allows it to make $14$ tons of oranges in a year. This means, of course, they can’t produce any hoverboards. But what if they do the opposite? What if they devote all their resources to making hoverboards? Then they would be able to make $11$ hoverboards (but no oranges). "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Imagine you sit down to do some homework. You are having a blast writing the outline of an essay. The ideas are flowing like liquid gold and then, all of a sudden, your pen runs out of ink!  You shuffle through drawers, searching for another pen but, sure enough, it was the last one. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "In fact, scarcity is so important to the study of economics, it’s the fundamental question of economics: faced with scarcity, how do we decide what to produce, how to produce it, and who gets that production? "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Let’s consider a hypothetical country called Maxistan that only produces two goods: hoverboards and oranges. After all, what’s more fun to eat while riding a hoverboard than an orange? "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Let’s see what all this looks like visually. Figure 1 shows Maxistan’s two possible outputs. Point A shows what would happen if it devoted all its resources to making oranges and point B represents what would happen if they devoted all their resources to hoverboards."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Like many of the other models we will use, the PPC is a handy way of showing four important concepts: scarcity, opportunity costs, inefficiency, and economic growth, which is a pretty impressive thing for a two-dimensional picture to be able to do if you think about it."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Maxistan is not limited to just these two outcomes though, making *only* hoverboards or *only* oranges. They’d probably like to mix this up a bit. So what happens if they devote some of their resources to producing oranges and some of them to producing hoverboards? "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Of course, it’s pretty unreasonable that a country would *only* produce two goods, but we’re dealing with a fictional country, so let’s imagine it. In this instance, we have a practical reason to limit our question to two goods. A *PPC* (our new best friend) has only two axes, and so thinking in terms of two goods (one for each axis) is a good place to start.  "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "So how does this illustrate **scarcity**? This PPC shows the absolute limits of production (or, the most that could possibly be produced). "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The PPC is basically just a line that connects not just these four different combinations, but *all* of the combinations of good that they could possibly produce, as shown in Figure 3."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Think about a time when the economic notion of scarcity could help you think about something affecting your daily life today. There are only so many hours in a day, how do you divide your time? If someone added one more hour to a day, what would you do with it? Thinking like an economist, and using your understanding of scarcity, what would the best solution be for you?"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "This is where the PPC comes in. The PPC is a line that shows all of the different combinations of these goods that could be produced. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-macroeconomics-staging/holding-area-for-unruly-questions/non-ap-style-questions/a/12-how-does-the-ppc-show-scarcity</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "To you, this is an awful moment. Maybe you lost the opportunity to write down your best ideas! There goes your Pulitzer Prize! An economist would think about your situation slightly differently.  From an economist’s perspective, your lack of a new pen simply illustrates the principle of scarcity: resources (like ink) are finite. It’s the job of economics to try to explain how we cope with this harsh reality."
msgstr ""

