# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* Every point on the production possibilities curve represents an efficient use of resources, in that any reallocation of the inputs to production will not allow for more to be made of one good without making less of the other good."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid ""
"* Not all costs are monetary costs. Opportunity costs are usually expressed in terms of how much of another good, service, or activity must be given up in order to pursue or produce another activity or good.\n"
"* You might hear the fourth economic resource referred to as either entrepreneurship or technology. The terms are used interchangeably but mean the same thing: the ability to make things happen. Take the example of computers—a computer itself would be considered a good, but our ability to make computers would be considered technology.\n"
"* The word capital is used in everyday language to mean what  economists would call *financial capital*. If you see the word capital on its own in an economics context, it refers to *physical capital*—equipment, machinery, or tools used to produce goods and services. Physical capital is tangible, but financial capital isn't always so."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The PPC illustrates scarcity by showing the boundary or limit of what can be produced given the economic resources on hand. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The opportunity cost of moving from one point on the PPC to another is the amount of one good given up to make one more unit of the other good. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The opportunity cost of producing one good in terms of another can either be constant or increasing for each additional unit. If opportunity cost is constant, the PPC will be a straight line. If opportunity cost is increasing, the PPC will be curved (like the one shown above)."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Economic resources are scarce. Faced with this scarcity, we must choose how to allocate our resources. Every choice we make has a cost. Opportunity costs are what we give up by making one choice over another."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost">http://translate.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/ap-microeconomics-staging/basic-economics-concepts/production-possibilities-frontier/a/lesson-overview-scarcity-choice-and-opportunity-cost</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid ""
"Term | Definition \n"
"- | - | -\n"
"Scarcity | The fact that there is a limited amount of resources to satisfy unlimited wants\n"
"Economic resources | Things that are inputs to production of goods and services. There are four economic resources: land, labor, capital, and technology. Technology is sometimes referred to as entrepreneurship.\n"
"Land | Natural resources that are used in the production of goods and services. Some examples of *land* are lumber, raw materials, fish, soil, minerals, and energy resources.\n"
"Labor | Work effort used in the production of goods and services. Some examples are number of workers and number of hours worked.\n"
"Capital | Physical goods that are produced and used to produce other goods. Examples of *capital* would be machinery, technology, and tools such as computers; hammers; factories; robots; trucks, and trains used to transport goods; and other equipment employed in the production of a good or service.\n"
"Technology/entrepreneurship |  Two terms that are used interchangeably to describe the ability to combine the other productive resources into goods and services\n"
"Production possibilities curve (PPC) | A model that captures scarcity and opportunity costs of choices when faced with the possibility of producing two goods or services. Sometimes called a production possibilities frontier.\n"
"Opportunity cost | The value of the next best alternative to any decision you make\n"
"Inefficient use of resources | The underutilization of any of the four economic resources, sometimes called underemployment of resources. *Inefficient use of resources* can be represented in a PPC model by a point inside the the production possibilities curve itself."
msgstr ""

